narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: I learned how to play several gamelan instruments, and some cultural context for the music/art form.
I learned a lot about Gamelan music and indonesian culture. got to learn new instruments in a welcoming, low pressure and engaging environment
I learned more about Indonesian culture and got to connect with a new community of people through music.
I learned how to play various instruments in a gamelan ensemble

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: The class was enjoyable and well structured! I would have appreciated some informal assessments/quizzes to ensure we learned more about the names of the instruments and the basics of the art form.

Strengths: great music, teaching, community, well organized, Phil cares a lot about explaining context.
Weaknesses: Sometimes the ordering and flow of pieces was a bit confusing to follow
The course is very flexible and playing the instruments is fairly straightforward, but it can sometimes be a struggle to understand the timing of gamelan.

Strength: it's a low-stakes class where you get to learn a way of playing music that's very different from Western music. It's fun and you get to play with beautiful instruments. Weakness: can't think of anything

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: Absolutely! This class was so fun and a great new type of challenge.
YES! Take this course if you can. It's an amazing class and something that is so uniquely "Yale"!
This course was a good place to work other parts of my brain and enjoy music.
Yes! It's a great fifth class and you learn by doing/trying/failing, which is a nice break from all the intellectualizing that happens in most other yale classes
